"rishi", hanging consonant "t" at the end of "p=
rachodayaat" etc. Most people do not pronounce these correctly. These occur=
 
in simple words, as opposed to this anuswara which occurs in complex 
Ved=
a mantras only. There are several such things where no single region 
of In=
dia got it right. Different parts of India are correct in different things.=


Fortunately, the correct pronunciation of all these 
sounds is confidentl=
y and accurately derivable based on grammar rules 
etc, if only one applies=
 oneself and thinks straight. Over the years, I have identified several of =
these, convinced myself 100% on 
each (except the anuswara where I am not 1=
00% sure) and switched my 
pronunciation accordingly.

However, now I am 10=
0% convinced that pronunciation 
is only 1% of the thing and devotion and s=
incerity are far more 
important, though correct pronunciation may be initi=
ally useful.

So I am not that motivated to correct people's pronunciation.=
 But, given that 
several insights came to me on this over the years, it is=
 probably one 
of my dharmas to share them with the world before I leave. I=
 will try to do it soon. I thought of making a youtube video on "pronunciat=
ion of tricky Sanskrit sounds" many years ago (showing my face and a white =
board). Perhaps time has come to just do it.

