Coming back to this anuswara:

Bindu before p, ph, b,=
 bh is pronounced as one nasal (m);bindu before t, th, d, dh is pronounced =
as another nasal (n); bindu before k, kh, g, gh is pronounced as another na=
sal; bindu before ch, chh, j, jh is pronounced as another nasal, etc.

My t=
ake is that bindu before y, r, l, v, sh, Sh, s, h is to be pronounced as th=
e first one again, i.e. as the nasal before k, kh, g, gh.

Take the mantra =
"tanno nArasi{M}haH prachodayAt", where {M} is this anuswara. A lot of scho=
lars pronounce this as "tanno nArasiguMhaH prachodayAt". IMHO, that is way =
off and has an extra syllable. You are better off just pronouncing it as "t=
anno nArasimhaH prachodayAt", i.e. pronounce {M} as "m" or the nasal before=
 p, ph, b, bh.

But better IMHO is to pronounce it as the nasal before g. S=
tart off as though you are saying "tanno nArasinghaH prachodayAt", suppress=
 "g" when about to say it, and jump directly to "h". That is what I do. Thi=
s allows you to pronounce the correct nasal. Unless we are about to say, k,=
 kh, g or gh, we can't say that nasal. Of course, in some languages (e.g. V=
ietnamese), that nasal occurs independently and those people can pronounce =
it well.

BTW, if you end up letting out a bit of "g" instead of suppressin=
g it completely and jumping to "h", then you end up getting "singha", which=
 is another common corruption of "si{M}ha".

To put it simply: The correct =
pronunciation is neither "sinha" nor "simha" nor "singha". It is "sin(g)ha"=
 with g silent.

